<div class="ds-eyebrow">foundations · responsive</div>
<h1 class="ds-title">Responsive layouts</h1>
<p class="ds-lede">Curie is a dark, desktop-first product. Responsiveness is delivered by a single stylesheet — <code>responsive.css</code> — that is the only file in the system containing <code>@media</code> queries. Below the mobile breakpoint each golden page swaps its desktop chrome for a purpose-built mobile view; at desktop width nothing here applies, so the desktop render is byte-for-byte unchanged.</p>

<h2 class="ds-section">Breakpoint tokens</h2>
<p class="ds-meta-line">Declared in <code>tokens.css</code>. Media-query conditions can't read <code>var()</code>, so these mirror the literal px values repeated in <code>responsive.css</code> — the same byte-stable pattern the rest of the system uses. Only <code>max-width</code> queries are used, so every rule activates <em>below</em> a breakpoint.</p>
<table class="ds-token-table">
  <thead><tr><th>Token</th><th>Value</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td><code>--bp-mobile</code></td><td><code>600px</code></td><td>At/below → full mobile shell (app bar + tab bar + FABs + mobile view)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>--bp-tablet</code></td><td><code>900px</code></td><td>At/below → dense desktop grids relax to 2 / 1 columns</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>--bp-desktop</code></td><td><code>1200px</code></td><td>Desktop reference tier (informational)</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2 class="ds-section">How it works</h2>
<div class="ds-usage-grid">
  <div class="ds-usage do"><strong>The model</strong>Each golden page ships its untouched desktop content <em>and</em> a hand-built mobile view (<code>.m-view</code>). A base guard sets every <code>.m-*</code> element to <code>display:none</code>; inside <code>@media (max-width:600px)</code> the desktop content is hidden and the mobile layer shown.</div>
  <div class="ds-usage dont"><strong>The invariant</strong>Nothing outside a <code>max-width</code> block ever changes desktop pixels. Shell/nav rules are scoped to <code>body[class^="pg-"]</code> so they never leak into the docs chrome or component preview iframes.</div>
</div>

<h2 class="ds-section">Mobile chrome anatomy</h2>
<div class="ds-anatomy">
  <code>.m-appbar</code><code>.m-tabbar</code><code>.m-tab.is-active</code><code>.m-drawer</code><code>.m-sheet</code><code>.m-fab--verify</code><code>.m-fab--action</code><code>.m-fab__dial</code><code>.m-view</code>
</div>
<ul class="ds-list">
  <li><strong>Top app bar</strong> (<code>.m-appbar</code>) — logo left · centered page title + emoji · hamburger (list pages) or back arrow (detail pages).</li>
  <li><strong>Bottom tab bar</strong> (<code>.m-tabbar</code>) — five destinations (Home · Briefs · Games · Editorial · Newsletter); the current tab carries <code>.is-active</code>. Absent on detail pages.</li>
  <li><strong>Drawer</strong> (<code>.m-drawer</code>) — full-screen glass overlay opened by the hamburger.</li>
  <li><strong>Bottom sheet</strong> (<code>.m-sheet</code>) — slide-up panel for Filters and other pickers.</li>
  <li><strong>FABs</strong> (<code>.m-fab</code>) — persistent verify button (bottom-left) + a contextual share/pulse action (bottom-right) with an optional <code>.m-fab__dial</code> speed-dial.</li>
</ul>

<h2 class="ds-section">Responsive grids</h2>
<p class="ds-meta-line">The five card grids step down by tier — <code>repeat(3,1fr)</code> desktop → 2-up at <code>≤900px</code> → single column at <code>≤600px</code> — expressed as mobile-only overrides so desktop track computation is untouched.</p>

<h2 class="ds-section">Live mobile previews</h2>
<p class="ds-meta-line">Each golden page rendered at a 390px viewport. These are the same files as the desktop <a href="/examples/">page examples</a> — one file, two layouts.</p>
<div class="ds-phone-row">
  {% set phones = [
    {file: "index.html", name: "Home"},
    {file: "briefs.html", name: "Briefs"},
    {file: "brief-detail.html", name: "Brief detail"},
    {file: "editorial.html", name: "Editorial"},
    {file: "editorial-detail.html", name: "Editorial detail"},
    {file: "newsletter.html", name: "Newsletter"},
    {file: "games.html", name: "Games"}
  ] %}
  {% for p in phones %}
  <figure class="ds-phone">
    <div class="ds-phone__screen"><iframe src="/examples/pages/{{ p.file }}" title="{{ p.name }} mobile" loading="lazy"></iframe></div>
    <figcaption>{{ p.name }}</figcaption>
  </figure>
  {% endfor %}
</div>

<style>
  .ds-phone-row { display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 28px; margin-top: 20px; }
  .ds-phone { margin: 0; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 10px; align-items: center; }
  .ds-phone__screen {
    /* content-box so the 390px is the true inner viewport. The docs set a global
       * { box-sizing: border-box }, which would otherwise make the 8px border eat
       into the 390px — shrinking the inner area to 374px and clipping the 390px
       iframe's right edge, so every preview card showed 22px left / 6px right. */
    box-sizing: content-box;
    width: 390px; height: 704px; border-radius: 28px; overflow: hidden;
    border: 8px solid #241f3d; box-shadow: 0 18px 50px rgba(0,0,0,0.45);
    background: #140d2c;
  }
  .ds-phone__screen iframe { width: 100%; height: 100%; border: 0; display: block; }
  .ds-phone figcaption { font-size: 12px; letter-spacing: .08em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--text-muted, #b3a6c8); }
</style>
